John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizens
Scottish Independent Schools maintain a trajectory of academic excellence that has continued in 2018 with another series of excellent exam results, which is reinforced by individual and collective success in sports, art, music and other community efforts.
With more than 30,000 pupils across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the highest level of service to pupils and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare students for further and higher studies, for the career they choose and for their place as citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a personalized school curriculum, we observe that modern languages remain a very popular and desired subject of choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, you will get to his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, you will reach his heart.”
This is a very important reminder that we cannot rely on English alone if we want to build relationships and build trust with people from other countries.
From the recent results of this year's exams, we can see that languages lead the ranking tables with the highest ratings in independent schools.
68% of students who studied foreign languages scored A higher.
The data, collected from 74 SCIS member schools, reflected that 72% of students obtained a higher A grade in Mandarin, while 72% of German students, 69% of French students and 63% of Spanish students also obtained an A.
This shows that Scottish independent schools support foreign languages as vital skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Currently, languages, as the subject of choice, are kept in the same consideration as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curricula of independent schools and elsewhere.
A 2014 survey by the UK Employment and Skills Commission revealed that of the reasons employers gave for the cost of filling vacancies, 17% were attributed to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly indispensable to prepare young people for their future careers.
As there are more and more potential job opportunities that require languages, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of which career a person chooses, if they have learned a second language, they will have a real advantage in the future with a permanent competition like this.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically puts a multilingual person ahead of the competition.
According to a 2013 survey by YouGov of more than 4,000 UK adults, 75% did not speak a foreign language well enough to hold a conversation, and French, with 15% of speakers, was the only language with a double-digit percentage.
For this reason, investing in language teaching is important for children today.
Knowing several languages, especially those of developed economies, will give children better opportunities to find an important job.
In Scotland there is diversity among schools in terms of the languages taught.
Some schools focus more on more traditional modern languages, while others teach languages that are believed to be more important to the UK for the future, by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever the interest of your child, you can always choose from a series of languages in independent schools, which have teaching staff specialized in this field.
Scottish Independent Schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that will prepare children and equip them with the skills necessary to succeed, regardless of what the future holds.
In today’s global business environment, it cannot be denied that languages continue to be of vital importance for the future of the country, and this must be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should really be considered “international communicative competences”.
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to Scottish youth.
We have to do it right.
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
