Harvard students take a course on rest habits
This year, a new course at Harvard University has allowed its students to sleep more, in an attempt to combat the culture, increasingly widespread, of studying throughout the night, stimulated by caffeine.
One academic noted that students at the world’s number one university are often misled as to the basics of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to create the course after giving a talk about the impact that sleep deprivation had on learning.
"At the end of the talk, a girl came up to me and said, 'Why are you telling me now, all this, in my last year?'
He said no one had ever talked to him about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, implemented for the first time this year, explains to students the basics of how good sleep habits improve academic and sports performance, in addition to overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the University’s health services, said the University decided to introduce the course after learning that some students suffered severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The course, which lasts one hour, includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one section there is an image of a bedroom, where students have to click on coffee cups, curtains, bamboos and books to receive information about the effects of caffeine and light, about how sports performance affects lack of sleep, and about the importance of maintaining a sleeping routine.
In another section, participants are told how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression, and cancer.
Next, a campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily route.
“We know that the behavior of the students will not change immediately.
But we believe they have a right to know, as one has a right to know the health effects of smoking cigarettes,” said Professor Czeisler.
The culture of pride in staying up all night still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and the growing pressure on students make sleep deprivation an ever-increasing problem.
Making sure you enjoy good quality sleep for long enough should be a student’s “secret weapon” to combat stress, fatigue and anxiety, he added, even to avoid gaining weight, as sleep deprivation puts the brain in starvation mode and makes students always hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemistry and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course, having attended one of his classes last year during his first year at Harvard.
Raymond commented that the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to promote the course throughout the campus.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask graduate students to complete a similar program of study before joining the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students be mindful of setting an alarm when they go to sleep and when they wake up, and that they be aware of the harmful effects of “blue light” emitted by electronic screens and LED lights, which can alter the harmony of the circadian rhythm and cause sleep problems.
