Almanac: the inventor of the Geiger counter
And now a page of the "Sunday Morning" Almanac: September 30, 1882, 136 years ago and counting... the day the physicist of the future, Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger, was born in Germany.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity, an invention that eventually resulted in the device we know as the "Geiger counter".
The Geiger Counter, which has been a pillar of science ever since, also became a staple of pop culture, as in the 1950 film "Bells of Coronado", starring Roy Rogers and Dale Evans, seemingly unsuccessful cowboy physicists:
Man: "What the hell is this?"
Rogers: "It's a Geiger counter, which is used to find radioactive minerals, such as uranium.
When you put on these headphones, you can hear the effects of the atoms that emanate from the radioactivity in the minerals."
Evans: "I'm sure it's bursting now!"
"Hans" Geiger died in 1945, a few days after his 63rd birthday.
The invention that bears his name is still alive.
New Cancer Vaccine May Teach Immune System to ‘See’ Malignant Cells
New Cancer Vaccine May Teach the Immune System to ‘See’ and Eliminate Malignant Cells
Vaccine teaches the immune system to recognize malignant cells as part of treatment
The method involves the extraction of immune cells from a patient and altering them in the laboratory.
You can “see” a protein common to many cancers and then reinject them
A test vaccine is showing promising results in patients with various types of cancers.
A woman treated with the vaccine, which teaches the immune system to recognize malignant cells, saw her ovarian cancer disappear for more than 18 months.
The method involves the extraction of immune cells from a patient, altering them in the laboratory to be able to "see" a protein present in many types of cancer (HER2), and subsequently re-injecting them.
According to Professor Jay Berzofsky of the National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, Maryland: “The results we have obtained suggest that we have a promising vaccine.”
The HER2 protein “favors the growth of several types of cancer,” including breast, ovarian, lung and colorectal cancers, Berzofsky said.
A similar approach to extracting immune cells from patients and “teaching” these cells how to treat cancer cells has worked in the treatment of a type of leukemia.
