HIV/AIDS: China reports 14% increase in new cases
China has announced a 14% increase in the number of citizens living with HIV and AIDS.
There are more than 820,000 people affected in the country, according to health officials.
In the second quarter of 2018 alone, 40,000 new cases were reported.
The vast majority of new cases are sexually transmitted, unlike in the past.
Traditionally, HIV was spreading rapidly in some regions of China due to infected blood transfusions.
However, the number of people contracting HIV from this cause has fallen to almost zero, according to statements by Chinese health workers at a conference in Yunnan province.
Year after year, however, the number of people living with HIV and AIDS in China has increased to 100,000 people.
Sexual transmission of HIV is a serious problem for China’s LGBT community.
Homosexuality was decriminalized in China in 1997, but discrimination against the LGBT community is common.
Considering the conservative values of the country, studies estimate that between 70 and 90 percent of men who have homosexual relationships will end up marrying a woman.
Many of the transmissions of diseases are due to the lack of adequate precautions for sexual intercourse.
Since 2003, the Chinese government has promised universal access to HIV medication as part of an effort to address the problem.
