The study by scientists at the National Foundation of Scotland will follow soprano and common bats, as well as northern ear bats and water bats at the Inverewe Botanical Garden, located at Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed at key locations on the property to keep track of bat activities during the season.
Volunteers and staff from the UK’s National Health Service will also conduct mobile surveys with portable detectors.
Sound analysis of the recordings by experts will determine the sound frequency of bats and what each species does.
With this information, a report and a map of the habitat will be created to create a detailed landscape-scale image of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, a conservation adviser at the National Foundation of Scotland, hopes the results will show which areas of the habitat are most important for bats and how each species uses them.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as grassland creation, and how to improve forest maintenance for bats and other associated species.
The bat population in Scotland and the rest of the United Kingdom has declined considerably in the last century.
Construction and restoration of buildings threaten bats, as they affect nests and can cause habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lighting also pose a risk, as do fly paper and chemical treatments used in building materials, as well as domestic cat attacks.
In reality, bats are not blind.
However, because of their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when they have to catch a prey.
They use a sophisticated echo localization technique to locate insects and obstacles that stand in their way.
The National Foundation of Scotland, responsible for taking care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes bats very seriously.
It has ten experts with the proper training, who carry out surveys, nest inspections and sometimes rescues on a regular basis.
The organization has even created Scotland’s first and only bat reserve at Threave Estate, located in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland’s ten bat species.
