“Here at Threave, we have a great area for bats,” he says.
“We have old buildings, a lot of old trees and a whole lot of good habitat.
But we are still unaware of many aspects of bats, so the work we do here and at other properties will help us better understand what they need to grow.”
It highlights the importance of checking bats before performing maintenance tasks on properties, as it may be that the possible involuntary destruction of a single maternity nest kills more than 400 females and young, which could lead to the disappearance of an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, attack, harass and destroy their nests.
Elisabeth Ferrell, an officer at the Scottish Bat Conservation Foundation, has encouraged people to take a step forward to help.
“We still have a lot to learn from bats and, in the case of some of our species, we don’t have enough data on their population.”
