How the U.S.-China Trade War Can Benefit Beijing
The initial salvos of the trade war between the US and China were deafening, and while the war does not appear to end soon, a distancing of the countries may prove beneficial to Beijing in the long run, experts say.
U.S. President Donald Trump issued his first warning earlier this year when he imposed taxes on major Chinese exports such as solar panels, steel and aluminum.
The most significant escalation occurred this week, with new tariffs affecting USD 200 billion worth of goods. These tariffs entail a taxation on half of all goods arriving in the US from China.
Beijing has counter-attacked each time in the same way and recently raised tariffs from five percent to ten percent for $60 billion of U.S. goods.
China has pledged to replicate the US and the world’s second-largest economy is unlikely to back down anytime soon.
Making Washington backwards involves yielding to some demands, but publicly bowing to the U.S. would be too embarrassing for Xi Jinping, the president of China.
However, experts say that if Beijing plays its cards well, the pressures of the trade war with the US could benefit China in the long run by reducing the interdependence of the two economies.
“The fact that a quick political decision in Washington or Beijing could create the conditions that initiate a fall in either of these countries is far more dangerous than witnesses had predicted,” said Abigail Grace, an associate researcher focused on Asia at the Center for New American Security, a panel of experts.
Syria is 'ready' for refugees to return, Foreign Minister says
Syria says it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and calls for help to rebuild the country, devastated by a war of more than seven years.
Speaking before the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem said conditions in the country are improving.
“Currently, the situation on the street is more stable and safe, thanks to the progress that has been made in the fight against terrorism,” he said.
The government continues to rehabilitate the areas that the terrorists destroyed to restore normalcy.
All conditions are met for the voluntary return of refugees to the country they had to leave because of terrorism and unilateral economic measures affecting their daily lives and their maintenance.
The EU estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have fled the country since the start of the war in 2011.
There are also six million people living in the country and in need of humanitarian aid.
Al-Moualem said the Syrian regime appreciates any help to rebuild the devastated country.
But he stressed that he would not accept conditional aid or aid from the countries that financed the insurgency.
