Red tide update: concentrations are reduced in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general reduction in red tide concentrations in certain parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, more scattered proliferation conditions are being reported in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier, suggesting a lower concentration.
Red tide proliferation extends along approximately 200 km of coastline, from northern Pinellas to the southern counties of Lee.
Spots can be found 16 km off the coast of Hillsborough county, but in fewer places, compared to last week's situation.
The red tide has also been observed in Pasco County.
Average coastal or remote coastal concentrations have been reported in Pinellas County over the past week, concentrations of low to high coastal or remote coastal concentrations in Hillsborough County, concentrations of low to high coastal or remote coastal concentrations in Manatee County, concentrations of low to low coastal or remote coastal concentrations in Charlotte County, concentrations of low to high coastal or remote coastal concentrations in Charlotte County.
Respiratory irritations continue to be reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
No respiratory irritation has been reported over the past week in northeast Florida.
